<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the National Motorist Action Group (CYS0030)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the National Motorist Action Group (CYS0030)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policy makers, government officials, the media and society in general has developed a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">blind-spot with regard to the significant number of cyclists who’s behaviours have such a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> negative impact on cycling road safety.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Two logically disjointed road safety regimes have grown up.  A regulation and enforcement heavy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for licensed motorists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and an ’anything goes’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  This is counterproductive for an optimal, unified road safety </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In urban centres, growing antagonism between the two factions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – motor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ists and cyclists, has meant that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">courteous co-operation between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> us</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ers has been replaced by an often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gladiatorial style </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">battle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Toleration, and in some cases, encouragement of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cyclists’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">law breaking has allowed personal responsibility for risk to be replaced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by an abdication of responsibility and reckless</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> behaviours</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">me</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cyclists. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Mayor of London’s flagship </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">policy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">promotin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cycling includes officially supplied cycle routes that include numerous road traffic law contraventions that further encourage lawlessness by cyclists.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is dangerous confusion over the role</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of Coroners in establishing the circumstances of fatal accidents with the result that a clear understanding of the issues </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potentially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">never emerges.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About NMAG</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The National Motorists Action Group (NMAG) is a motorists’ representative and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lobbying group set up in 2011 to represent the interests of the UK’s 36 million driving licence holders.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG also has a remit to promote, support and initiate lega</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l actions to challenge the law; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the interpretation of the law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the unlawful exercise of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">administrative powers that are to the detriment of motorists.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the Writer</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rupert Lipton is Managing Director of NMAG and has prepared this submission.  He is perhaps uniquely qualified to comment on the matters here, having spent 10 years, up until Se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ptember 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as a professional driver based in London, initially as a motorcycle despatch </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rider and latterly as a Gov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ernment Car Service Ministerial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Security </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Driver.  He is an accredited Police Advanced Driver.  He is also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a recently qualified barrister</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">non-practising) and former amateur racing cyclist.  He regularly walks around central London and is an occasional user of the Barclays Cycle Hire scheme.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission is endorsed by the NMAG board of directors.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">NMAG’s interest in Cycling Safety</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Quite apart from recognising that very many cyclists will also be motorists and that the overall issue of road safety is of critical concern to motorists and citizens in general, NMAG’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">interest in the topic derives from the way that motorists are routinel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y demonised in such matters of road safety and a belief that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the issue well illustrates a fundamental malaise in the way that local and national government policy is developed in regard to road safety.  Motorists generically are unfairly and disproporti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ona</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tely taxed, fined, penalised and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> blamed by society (despite such a large proportion of adult society being motorists), with the result that increasingly bad policy, based on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ‘CAR BAD – BICYCLE GOOD’ group-think </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Society has been suff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ering from a worrying blind-spot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with regard to cyclists’ own contribution to cycling road safety (or lack thereof).  Whilst in recent days, this issue has been part of the public debate, thanks in part to the Mayor of London’s comments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for which he was r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oundly condemned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the previous failure of politicians, journalists and commentators to even consider the culpability of cyclists in their own </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accident statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has been a truly shocking phenomenon.  This point is sadly illustrated by the Transport Commi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ttee’s complete failure to even mention the issue in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2012 Road Safety Report.  This despite the fact that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the widespread abuse of road traffic laws by urban cyclists is plain for all in London to see</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG has valuable experience of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inquest </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by which society </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be able to best understand the causative factors of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">serious </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cycle accidents and therefore learn appropriate lessons.  It appears that this process is potentially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">afflicted by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the same </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">blind-spot.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG would like to stress that the points made here, in limited space, should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be taken to diminish in anyway the undoubted shortcomings of some motorists’ behaviours on the road; the need for proper sanctions against all culpable road users; the need f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or ongoing driver and cyclist training; or the development of better infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to aid all road users to stay safe.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG also acknowledges the advantages that cycling has over other forms of transport in terms of environmental and health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> benefits to all of society.  These however are a separate matter of policy from road safety and should not be allowed to cloud the issue.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Key Submissions</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Driving Licence Holders’ Road Safety v Cyclists’ Road Safety</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The safety of road users </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> surely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a single</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unified </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">topic.  The safety of one set of road users cannot realistically be considered without reference to another’s.  After all, the number of cyclists killed and seriously injured in collisions involving only other cyclists is presumably lo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">w.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">And yet, in as much as Highways and Road Traffic law is predicated on prevention of accidents, which it surely largely is, there appears to be no unity of thought on the matter.  How can it be that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> whilst motorists are required to comply with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a regime t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat includes the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> driving test; driving licenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vehicle licence; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MOT; penalty points; and compulsory insurance, cyclists are not only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">largely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">left to thei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r own choices and responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but also apparently, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">llowed to develop a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> widespread understandi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng that the road traffic laws do not apply to them?  It is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">said</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that greater responsibility accrues to those in charge of motorised vehicles, because of the sheer weight, speed and potential for damage that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they may inflict</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but from the point of view of o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">utcomes, it is incredible that the group of road users who are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">most vulnerable are the very ones to whom a regime designed to promote road safety is seemingly NOT targeted.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is submitted that in London at least, a cyclist riding the wrong way </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">up a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one-way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> street, at night, without lights is exceedingly unlikely to be stopped by the police or sanctioned in any way.  The writer lives in a fourth storey flat overlooking a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one-way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> street in central London.  For reasons of road layout, not less than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 100 cyclists, probably far more, cycle the wrong way down this busy road</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> every day</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  At the far end of the road (if travelled in the correct direction) is a police station and associated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">police </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vehicle yard.  Accordingly very many marked police vehicles t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ravel down this road.  In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> five years, the writer has NEVER seen the police stop any such cyclists and has on at least 10 occasions witnessed police vehicle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> passing such transgressing cyclist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Meanwhile, motorists are ruthlessly penalised, by CCTV, for m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inor and often accidental transgressions, such as yellow box offences, that are not even matters of road safety.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Government should make plain its intention to rebalance this situation, firmly encouraging Police Forces to take seriously the enforcement of road traffic regulations for cyclists.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> (And not just in the wake of a spate of deaths).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  At the same time, as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">is already mooted, the excessive enforcement by local highway authorities against motorists should be reined in.  Government should encourage a national debate on the matter and make plain the shared responsibility of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">road users for road safety.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ladiatorial Battle</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG believes that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> despite press </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focus on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> road rage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, drunk drivers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘boy racers’, the vast majority of motorists are responsible and cautious in their use of the public highway.  Indeed, drivers learn at the outset of their driving ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reer, not just the explicit rules of the road, but also the implied ones.  Motorists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">co-operate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with one another to a very large extent and there is an unwritten code of courtesy which is widely observed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The situation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">between</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> motorists and cyclists is dan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gerously different.  For a host of reasons touched on in this document, motorist v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ersu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s car, at least in London, has become gladiatorial.  The culture of cycling seems to be that inconveniencing motorists is a positively good thing to do.  At best, the cyc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">list is taking care of his or her needs, and the motorist can just put up with it.  Unsurprisingly, many otherwise considerate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">motorists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> do not feel inclined to be helpful to cyc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ists.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Add in the fact that a motorist knows that the chances of him being fin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed or penalised by the authorities are high,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> often via CCTV systems widely believed to be used primarily for revenue generation,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> whilst cyclists have a ‘free-run’ and the levels of antagonism rise to frightening levels.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Again, there is an extraordinary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">log</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ical disconnect here.  Motorists generally take a responsible approach to their road use – they do not want to injure themselves or others, whilst cyclists in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases, have been tacitly encouraged to behave quite recklessly and then expect to blame othe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rs for any misfortune that they suffer.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Government should put in place a communications campaign to prompt a step change in the relationship between motorists and cyclists.  If each group experience a positive change in att</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">itude from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">other, courtesy and co-operation could soon become the new road culture between them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cyclists’ Law Breaking</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There can be no doubt that law breaking by cyclists, at least in London and other urban centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is ende</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mic.  The writer has even seen Metropolita</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">olice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cycle patrols </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">riding on pavements and the wrong way down </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one-way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> streets.  It is clear that many cyclists believe that a no-right turn restriction does not actually apply to them.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (The writer has on a number of occasions challenged cyclists about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such offences).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Such a restriction is often in place specifically for reasons of road safety.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One has to have some sympathy with the many cyclists, policy makers and law enforcers who seem to have fallen into the belief that with cyclists, anything goes.  The current Prime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Minister</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was famously shown in national newspapers, flouting road </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">traffic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> la</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ws on a bicycle, during his time as leader of the opposition.  Other public figures who should know better, have been similarly caught out or tacitly suggested that cyclists should interpret (or ignore) the rules as they feel fit, where they believe that i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is ‘safer’ for them to do so.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG does not doubt that good arguments could be constructed that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> could be exempted from some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">road traffic laws, and would not necessarily be opposed to such a regime.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  However, it is presumably self-evident that cy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clists ignoring traffic lights or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one-way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> streets should only do so after parliament has considered the matter and not of their own volition.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are now a number of places in central London, where roads that previously suffered from large scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contrave</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one-way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> street, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ere simply re-designated as two-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">way </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">streets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for cyclists with NO change to the road layout or road markings.  At least there are now signs to alert motorists to the oncoming cyclists, but what message is sent out to cyclists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this is the response to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> such mass law breaking?</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is clearly a highly relevant question to be asked about the extent to which such contraventions by cyclists are causative of accidents.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some argue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that cyclists going through red traffic lights potenti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ally reduce danger for themselves at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> junction.  Why could this argument not be used with equal force for a moped, or motorcycle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or a car?  No one seriously suggests, that a car driver, waiting at a red light at a deserted junction, even one with good vi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sibility, should be allowed treat the red light as discretionary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – from that position chaos would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reign</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  As it now does with regard to cyclists in London!</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Former Labour Transport Secretary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(and cyclist) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lord Adonis recently stated in the media that only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> few percent of cycling accidents involve cyclists breaking the law.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has not been able to trace the genesis of this data, but it is suggested that it may accurately reflect the situation with regard to contraventions of specific orders and laws –</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> one</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">way street, red lig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hts, banned turns etc.  But what if dangerous and careless cycling (offences under the Road traffic Act 1988) are included?  Given that it seems that very few such offences are reported even where witnessed by police, how likely are we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to reliably know where cycle accidents did or did not involve such offences?</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many cyclists seem to passionately believe that the wearing of cycle helmets is of critical importance to them as a cyclist – an act of faith</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> perhaps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  There is research and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rguments that point the other way and clearly many cyclist injuries will occur irrespective of the wearing of a helmet.  Similarly, many cyclists choose to wear retro-reflective and other high visibility clothes whilst cycling.  Both these measures are pre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sumably taken </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by cyclists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the interests of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> safety.  And yet, bizarrely, many cyclists, often the very same cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are quite willing to ignore other road safety measures that happen to be legal requirements – like using lights in the dark or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> stopping at red traffic lights.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">How did we get to the stage that cyclists enthusiastically embrace helmets and yellow jackets, but simultaneously ignore statutory requirement such as lights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at night</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and road traffic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">signs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Government should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> make plain a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> backstop position of licensing for cyclists, if poor behaviour by a significant proportion of cyclists is not improved over the next few years.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Police forces should be encouraged to enforce existing laws relating to dangerous and careless cyc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ling.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Attitude of Authorities</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NMAG has shocking evidence of the dangerous a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ttitude London government has to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cyclists and the law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It is evidence that officials</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (and perhaps their political masters)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> responsible for the operational aspect of cycling management in London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> suffer from the same blind-spot with regard to cyclists’ contribution to their own </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">risk levels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In August of this year, the writer noticed that the Barclays Bikes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">smartphone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> App, promo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ted by Transport for London, was providing cycle routes for users that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">directed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> them the wrong way down one-way streets, compelled them to make illegal turns and to cycle on pavements and footways.  In one route from London N1 to Victoria Embankment, no fe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wer than eight unlawful manoeuvres were suggested.  The writer wrote to the Mayor of London and the Group Chairman of Barclays Bank about the matter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as well as the Commissioner of the Metropolitan Police and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Commiss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oner of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ity of London Police</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When no response was received from the Mayor, the writer made telephone enquiries and was told that the matter had been referred to Transport for London.  A response from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is still awaited.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A response was received from the Vice President of Sponsorship,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Brand and Marketing of Barclays, Jonathan Neill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in September 2013.  He explained that the route data was derived from ‘Cycle Streets’ who in turn use an open-source mapping project to provide the routes and that no map data could be 100% accurate.  He un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dertook to inform the map suppliers of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">illegalities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and indeed the problems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identified </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the mapping were rectified.  However, as the data is open source</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the routes continuously change and many of the illegal routes have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> since </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">returned or been replac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed by new illegal routes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A response was received at the end of Oc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tober from Cycling Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for London </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Andrew Gilligan who</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seemingly absolved the Mayor’s Office / </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from responsibility by stating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that Barclays were the ‘owners and creators’ of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Barclays Bikes App</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  However, Mr Gilligan also stated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TfL’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Cycle Journey Planner on its website ‘is kept accurate to comply with the most up to date information available with regards to road regulations and changes’.  The first r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oute that the writer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> looked at on the website,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whilst different fr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">om the Barclays Bikes App route</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, also directed cyclists to perform a number of illegal manoeuvres.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Quite apart from the immediate dangers of directing unwitting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and possibly inexperienced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cyclists the wrong way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> down one-way streets and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">other illegal manoeuvres, one can only imagine the potency of the message given to cyclists about complying with the law, when they find that routes supplied by or with the connivance of Transport for London, enjoin them to i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gnore road traffic rules.  And this is after the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and his sponsors, have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been alerted to the problem.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendation</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Government Guidance should make very plain to Highway Authorities their duties, in Road Traffic and Highways policy, to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">non-compliance with the law must not be promoted.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Understanding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the Cause of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Cycling Accidents</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The writer has long suspected that motorists in general have been ritualistically held to be the chief blame carriers for injuries to non-motorists in traffic accidents.  Long experience of comparing initial media reporting with official reports that emerg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e months later, has shown that vulnerable victims are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sometimes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at least in part to blame for their own accidents.  This is not intended to be inflammatory or to diminish the responsibility that should fairly be taken by motorists, but it is surely critica</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l to good policy making that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">real</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> facts are properly understood and reported.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this vein, when in mid-October 2013, the inquests were held into the deaths of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cyclists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Brian Dorling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Philippine de </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gerin-Ricard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at Bow roundabout in October 2011 and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Aldgate in July 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> respectively</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the writer followed the media reports with interest.  What appeared to emerge is that Miss de </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gerin-Ricard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> had contributed to the accident by cycling on the pavement but that she had not cycled recklessly.  In Mr Dorling’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s case, the Coroner’s sharp criticism of the layout of the cycle super highway on which he was cycling attracted all the media attention and little else as to the cause of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and responsibility for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the accident was reported.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The writer then saw a press report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in which Sir Peter Hendy, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TfL’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Transport Commissioner stated that Mr Dorling had cycled through a red light.  The writer had not seen this fact reported in coverage of the inquest and so contacted the Coroner to request a copy of the inquest’s findings f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or both deaths.  Because the Coroner had found that Article 2 of the European</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Convention of Human Rights (Right to Life) had not been engaged (despite finding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the State provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Cycle Super Highways </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">causative in both accidents), there was no req</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uirement to produce a narrative determination detailing the circumstances around the accidents.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (This being the scheme provided for by section 5 of the Coroners and Justice Act 2009).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Accordingly, the only formal information available to the public with r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">egard to Miss de </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gerin-Ricard’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> death was a finding of accidental death and the Prevention of Future Deaths Report concentrates on the infrastructure issues and makes no mention of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">culpability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for the accident.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the case of Mr Dorling, the Coro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ner </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">chose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to produce a narrative determination which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> gave a little more information.  Mr Dorling was cycling in lane one of two on approach to the roundabout.  The tipper truck which hit him was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">travelling in the same direction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in lane two.  The traffic wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s heavy.  As the traffic lights turned red, both vehicles went through the lights, Mr Dorling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">passing the truck on its inside</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and only briefly visible in the truck’s mirrors.  The truck turned left at the roundabout hitting Mr Dorling who was intending to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proceed straight on.  At this point any road user would surely consider the fundamental question – was the truck driver indicating his intention to turn left?  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Alarmingly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he determination is silent on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the matter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with the result that policy makers, governm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent officials, media commentators and the public at large are unable to conclude where the blame for this accident truly lies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The above inquest is of course only one of many.  It is used to illustrate another example of society’s blind-spot – that cyclist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s’ behaviours are not relevant to the matter of cyclist safety.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In fact there is potentially a deeper problem with the Inquests regime, in the tension that lies between the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expectation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (in some cases) that the circumstances around a death will be reveale</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d whilst blame or liability will not.  Where public policy is not directly involved it is understandable that the later will trump the former.  But in matters of road safety, and the enormous public responsibility of reducing danger on the roads, surely le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssons can only properly be learnt if inquests fully explore the question of how and why accidents happen.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One can only speculate as to the number of inquests similarly affected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as the October one appeared to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, although in the current media debate, it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clear that a widespread lack of information or understanding about the apportionment of responsibility generally has been very much informed by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> shortcomings.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>